```{r setup, include = FALSE}
knitr::opts_chunk$set(
  collapse = TRUE,
  fig.width = 7,
  fig.height = 4.5,
  fig.path = "fig/selection-",
  comment = "#>",
  message = FALSE,
  warning = FALSE
)
library(baggr)
```

This vignette shows a short workflow for assessing and adjusting for publication
bias in a meta-analysis. We use the vitamin A supplementation and child mortality
data from @imdad_vitamin_2022, included in _baggr_ as `vitamin_a`.

The outcome is the log risk ratio for all-cause child mortality. Negative values
indicate lower mortality in the vitamin A supplementation arm.

```{r}
head(vitamin_a)
summary(exp(vitamin_a$tau))
```

The studies are heterogeneous and vary substantially in precision. This is the
setting where small-study effects are especially important: if smaller studies
with favourable or statistically significant estimates are more likely to be
published, an ordinary random-effects model can overstate the average effect.
However, funnel asymmetry can also reflect genuine differences between study
settings, so the checks below should be read as sensitivity analyses rather than
automatic corrections.

# Funnel plot

First fit the usual Rubin summary-data model. We label the estimand as a log
risk ratio so that plots and summaries are easier to read.

```{r fit-unadjusted, include = FALSE}
set.seed(1990)
bg_va <- baggr(vitamin_a, effect = "log risk ratio",
               iter = 1000, chains = 2, refresh = 0)
```

```{r fit-unadjusted-code, eval = FALSE}
bg_va <- baggr(vitamin_a, effect = "log risk ratio")
```

```{r}
bg_va
```

A funnel plot compares study-level effects with their standard errors. In the
absence of small-study effects or unexplained heterogeneity, points should be
roughly symmetric around the pooled estimate.

```{r}
funnel(bg_va)
```

The dashed lines include both sampling uncertainty and the estimated
between-study heterogeneity. The plot is therefore a visual diagnostic, not a
test of publication bias by itself.

# Selection adjustment

Selection models make the publication process explicit. In _baggr_, `selection`
sets cut-points on the study z-statistic. The shorthand
`selection = 1.96` fits a symmetric two-sided model, splitting studies at the
usual 5 percent normal threshold, $|z| = 1.96$.

```{r fit-selection-simple, include = FALSE}
set.seed(1991)
bg_va_sel <- baggr(vitamin_a, selection = 1.96,
                   effect = "log risk ratio",
                   iter = 1000, chains = 2, refresh = 0)
```

```{r fit-selection-simple-code, eval = FALSE}
bg_va_sel <- baggr(vitamin_a, selection = 1.96,
                   effect = "log risk ratio")
```

```{r}
bg_va_sel
selection(bg_va_sel)
```

The `selection()` output reports the relative publication probability for the
lower `|z|` interval. The highest `|z|` interval is the reference category, fixed
to 1. Values below 1 mean that less statistically striking estimates are inferred
to be less likely to appear in the observed literature.

The same idea can be made more flexible by adding more thresholds. For example,
the following model separates results below 10 percent, between 10 and 5 percent,
between 5 and 1 percent, and beyond 1 percent on the usual two-sided normal
scale.

```{r fit-selection-multi, include = FALSE}
set.seed(1992)
bg_va_sel_multi <- baggr(vitamin_a, selection = c(1.64, 1.96, 2.58),
                         effect = "log risk ratio",
                         iter = 1000, chains = 2, refresh = 0)
```

```{r fit-selection-multi-code, eval = FALSE}
bg_va_sel_multi <- baggr(vitamin_a, selection = c(1.64, 1.96, 2.58),
                         effect = "log risk ratio")
```

```{r}
selection(bg_va_sel_multi)
```

For explicit control, pass a list with the z cut-points, whether the model is
symmetric, and which studies could have been selected. Here the model uses
one-sided z intervals. This is mainly useful when the direction of selection is
part of the substantive assumption.

```{r fit-selection-list, include = FALSE}
set.seed(1993)
selection_one_sided <- list(
  z = c(1.64, 1.96),
  symmetrical = FALSE,
  possible = rep(1, nrow(vitamin_a))
)
bg_va_sel_one_sided <- baggr(vitamin_a, selection = selection_one_sided,
                             effect = "log risk ratio",
                             iter = 1000, chains = 2, refresh = 0)
```

```{r fit-selection-list-code, eval = FALSE}
selection_one_sided <- list(
  z = c(1.64, 1.96),
  symmetrical = FALSE,
  possible = rep(1, nrow(vitamin_a))
)

bg_va_sel_one_sided <- baggr(vitamin_a, selection = selection_one_sided,
                             effect = "log risk ratio")
```

```{r}
selection(bg_va_sel_one_sided)
```

The important modelling choice is not the syntax, but the assumed selection
mechanism. With only a modest number of studies, selection models can be weakly
identified. In the vitamin A example, the adjustment is useful because it shows
how much the random-effects result depends on possible preferential publication
of more significant or favourable small-study estimates; it should not be treated
as definitive evidence about the exact publication process.

